## Project Dashboard

The Project Dashboard is a separate primary mode alongside the Writing Workspace. It is reached via a toolbar toggle — the Workspace and Dashboard share the same SwiftData container, the same book, the same entity database. Writing populates it; the Dashboard visualises and enriches it.

```
WelcomeWindow (book picker)
       │
       ├── WorkspaceView  ←  write prose, tag entities, build relationships
       │
       └── ProjectDashboard  ←  plan, research, visualise the world
                │
                ├── Timeline      dual-rail chronology
                ├── World Map     temporal map with entity pins
                ├── Mind Map      auto-generated relationship graph
                ├── Notes         linked rich-text research system
                └── Sheets        typed spreadsheets linked to notes
```

These tools are designed to be universal, supporting any novel genre through flexible customization.

---

### Timeline Tool

The Timeline is a dual-rail chronology display. The two rails coexist permanently in the view, one above the other, with connecting lines showing the relationship between them.

#### Rail 1 — Narrative Rail (Chapter Order)

The order in which the reader experiences the story. Fixed sequence: Chapter 1, Chapter 2, Chapter 3... regardless of when those events occur in story time. Every chapter always exists on this rail. This rail cannot be reordered.

```
Narrative Rail:
Ch.1 ──────── Ch.2 ──────── Ch.3 ──────── Ch.4 ──────── Ch.5
[Prologue]   [The War]    [Flashback]   [Present]    [Epilogue]
```

#### Rail 2 — Story Rail (In-World Chronological Time)

The actual calendar order of events in the story world. The author assigns an in-world date to each chapter. A non-linear narrative where Chapter 3 is a flashback to a different era will show Chapter 3's events far from Chapter 1's events on this rail, even though it comes later in the manuscript.

```
Story Rail (chronological):
1066        1944        1991        2026        2031
  ↓           ↓        ↓  ↓          ↓           ↓
[Ch.3]     [Ch.2]   [Ch.1][Ch.4]  [new event] [Ch.5]
```

#### Cross-Reference Lines

Connecting lines run between the two rails, mapping each chapter's narrative position to its story-time position. This instantly reveals structural information invisible in a linear chapter list: flashbacks, foreshadowing jumps, how much story-time a single chapter spans, gaps in the world timeline where no chapter takes place.

#### In-World Date Assignment

The author sets an in-world date per chapter in the Chapter List panel — a small date field below the chapter title. This is the only manual step required. Everything else on the Timeline is computed automatically.

#### Custom Calendar Systems

Worlds in any genre may use unique calendars. The author defines a custom calendar in the Dashboard Settings panel:

- Custom month names and lengths
- Era system (e.g. "Third Age, Year 412" instead of "2026 AD")
- Named epochs with start/end years
- Year zero definition

Once a calendar is defined, all in-world dates throughout the app — Timeline, Sheets, Entity details — display using the author's calendar. If no custom calendar is defined, the app defaults to numeric years.

#### Events on the Timeline

Beyond chapters, the author can stamp discrete **Events** on either rail:

On the **Story Rail**: world events that may not have their own chapter — a war that began 300 years before the story starts, a prophecy made in year 1 that Chapter 5 fulfills. These are created from within the Timeline view and stored as Event entity records.

On the **Narrative Rail**: Scene Stamps from the writing workspace (`⌘⌥(` / `⌘⌥)`) appear automatically as sub-markers within their parent chapter, no manual entry required.

#### Entity Arcs

Any entity can have a life arc drawn across both rails. A character arc shows:

- First mention in the manuscript (Narrative Rail position)
- Birth / origin date (Story Rail position)
- Key events in their life on the Story Rail
- Every chapter they appear in on the Narrative Rail

The arc is **generated automatically** from the entity tagging and relationship data the writer already created — no separate data entry. This is the primary advantage over Aeon Timeline, where all arc data must be entered manually. In StoryCompiler, the writing process is the data entry.

#### Filtering and Zoom

- Filter by entity type: show only character arcs, hide locations
- Filter by specific entities: show only one character's arc
- Filter by time range: zoom into a specific decade on the Story Rail
- Both rails have independent zoom levels
- The Narrative Rail always shows all chapters; the Story Rail can span millennia

