### World Map Tool

The World Map is a **temporal map** — it shows the world at a specific point in story time, and its state changes as the Story Rail timeline cursor is dragged.

The connection to the timeline is the defining feature. A territory that belonged to one kingdom in year 1066 may belong to a different kingdom in year 1991. If the author has tagged these territorial changes as Events on the Story Rail, the map reflects the change when the cursor crosses that date. This temporal aspect works for any genre, from a gangster moving between cities in a thriller to a knight traveling across kingdoms in fantasy or space pirates navigating galaxies in sci-fi. The map is scalable, depicting anything from an entire planet to a small town, and tracks entity movements throughout the story timeline.

#### Drawing Layers

The map is a multi-layer canvas:

- **Terrain layer** — coastlines, rivers, mountain ranges, forests. Drawn with freehand and shape tools.
- **Kingdoms layer** — territory polygons, colour-coded and labelled by Faction entity.
- **Locations layer** — named pins linked to Location entities in the database.
- **Routes layer** — roads, trade routes, travel paths. Optionally linked to Event entities.

Each layer can be toggled independently. Layers have temporal states — a kingdom polygon can have different boundaries at different Story Rail dates.

#### Entity Pins

Any entity of type Location, Character, or Faction can be pinned to map coordinates. Tapping a pin opens the entity's details in a popover. The Locations layer populates automatically from all Location entities in the database that have been assigned coordinates.

#### Story Rail Scrubbing

A scrubber bar at the bottom of the map view mirrors the Story Rail. Dragging it forward in time reveals how the map changes — borders shift, cities appear and are destroyed, routes open and close. The scrubber only shows changes the author has explicitly defined; it does not simulate or infer.

#### Export

The current map view at any Story Rail position can be exported as a PNG at print quality — for chapter illustrations, website headers, or sharing with readers.

---

### Mind Map Tool

The Mind Map is a relationship graph generated automatically from the entity and relationship database. It is the visual representation of everything the writer has built through Subject Lock and Define Relationship sessions.

#### Auto-Generated Graph

- Every **Entity** record is a node, colour-coded by entity type
- Every **EntityRelationship** record is a directed edge, labelled with the predicate text the author wrote
- The graph updates in real time as new relationships are created in the workspace

This is the primary advantage over Obsidian's graph view: the nodes are typed, the edges are labelled with the author's own language, and the entire structure was built as a byproduct of writing — not by manually building a knowledge graph.

#### Filtering

- By entity type (show only characters and factions, hide locations)
- By chapter (show only the relationship web that exists as of a specific chapter)
- By predicate keyword (show only edges containing "fear" or "trained")
- By entity (isolate one entity and show its entire relationship neighbourhood)

#### Manual Brainstorming Canvas

Alongside the auto-generated graph, the author can create blank Mind Map canvases for freeform brainstorming. Manual nodes and edges on a brainstorming canvas are not connected to the entity database — they are scratch thinking. These canvases save as Note objects scoped to the book.

This tool is versatile for any genre, visualizing complex relationships like alliances in sci-fi, betrayals in thrillers, or family ties in romance.

---

### Notes System

The Notes system is the research and lore layer of the Project Dashboard. The design target is Apple Notes — fast, frictionless, fully featured, rich text — with one capability Apple Notes does not have: every note can link bidirectionally to any entity in the worldbuilding database.

#### What a Note Contains

- Title
- Rich text body: bold, italic, headers, bullet lists, numbered lists, code blocks, inline images
- Optional folder for organisation
- Optional tags (user-defined keywords, separate from entity tags)
- Optional chapter anchor (note appears in Chapter List context when that chapter is open)
- Optional entity links (one or more entities this note is about)
- Pin state (pinned notes appear at top of list)
- Creation and modification timestamps
- Colour label (seven colours, user-assigned)

#### Entity Linking

Typing `@EntityName` inside a note body creates a live link to that entity. The link renders as a coloured inline span matching the entity's type colour. Tapping the link navigates to the entity's detail panel.

The reverse is also true: the Entity Details panel shows a **Linked Notes** section listing every note that references that entity. The author can navigate freely between entity details and the notes about that entity without losing context.

#### Note Categories

There are no enforced categories — a note is a note. The author organises their own system using folders and tags. Common uses include:

- **Research notes** — real-world historical research about cultures, technologies, eras
- **Lore documents** — magic systems, cosmology, physics of the world
- **Character profiles** — deep backstory, psychology, motivations beyond what fits in the entity notes field
- **Language notes** — vocabulary lists, grammar rules, example sentences for constructed languages
- **Culture briefs** — customs, religion, social structure of a faction or heritage group
- **Worldbuilding reference** — geography, climate, trade routes, political history

#### Embedded Sheets

A note can embed a Sheet inline — a vocabulary table, a cast of characters, a timeline of events. The embedded sheet is a live SwiftData Sheet record, not a static snapshot. Editing the sheet from within the note updates it everywhere.

#### Relationship to the Workspace

Notes are accessible from the Dynamic Panel in the writing workspace. When the Dynamic Panel is in its default (idle) state, it shows the Notes navigator for the current book. The author can consult and edit research notes without leaving the writing environment.

This system is applicable to any genre, providing a flexible space for research and planning.

---

### Sheets Tool

Sheets are typed spreadsheets scoped to a book. They are reference tables — not a calculation engine, not a database replacement. The author uses them for structured lists where a prose note would be too unstructured and a database query would be too technical.

#### Cell Types

Every column has a declared type:

- **Text** — plain or rich text string
- **Number** — integer or decimal
- **In-World Date** — uses the book's custom calendar definition if set, otherwise numeric year
- **Entity Link** — a live link to any entity record; displays the entity name and type badge
- **Note Link** — a live link to any note; displays the note title

#### Preset Templates

On creation, the author can choose a blank sheet or a preset template:

- **Character Roster** — Name, Age, Faction, Role, First Appearance (chapter), Last Appearance, Status (alive/dead/unknown), Notes link
- **Timeline Events** — In-World Date, Event Name, Involved Entities, Chapter (if any), Importance
- **Vocabulary** — Word, Translation, Grammatical Class, Language (entity link), Etymology Notes link
- **World History** — In-World Date, Era, Event, Kingdoms Involved, Source Notes link
- **Custom** — start from a blank grid with user-defined columns

Templates are starting points only — every column can be renamed, retyped, reordered, added, or removed.

#### CSV Export

Any sheet can be exported as CSV for use in external tools, sharing, or archiving.

Sheets are versatile tools for organizing data in any novel project, from character inventories in fantasy to plot timelines in mysteries.

