## Design Principles

**Harvest, don't re-enter.** The writer already expresses context through tagging. The app harvests what's already there rather than asking for it again in a separate form.

**The writer steers.** The app never guesses what a relationship means. Every relationship in the database was put there by an explicit writer action.

**Two modes, one database.** The Writing Workspace and Project Dashboard are two views of the same data. Writing populates the entity database; the Dashboard visualises it. Neither mode duplicates data entry.

**The timeline reflects the manuscript.** The dual-rail Timeline is generated from the writing — chapter order is fixed by the manuscript, in-world dates are set by the author once per chapter, entity arcs emerge from the tagging. The author does not maintain a separate timeline document.

**The map reflects the story.** The World Map is temporal. It does not show one fixed state — it shows the world at any point in story time the author navigates to. Territory, borders, and events change as the story timeline advances.

**Seed data as training wheels.** Entity types, predicate suggestions, and sheet templates all ship with sensible defaults on day one. They get out of the way as the writer builds their own vocabulary. They are never enforced.

**Free text over fixed lists.** Predicates, note bodies, and sheet column definitions are all plain English in the writer's own voice. No dropdowns. No validation rules. If the writer can express it in a sentence, the app can store it.

**The database writes itself.** By the time a manuscript is finished, the worldbuilding database is complete — not because the writer filled in forms, but because the writing process itself was the data entry.

